<center>
<h1>   Particles in the  upper Troposphere and lower 
  Stratosphere  and their role in the climate system (PARTS)</h1>
   <p><hr>

   <p>Welcome to the University of Oxford <A HREF="http://www.atm.ox.ac.uk/main/dept/index.html">AOPP</A> page of <A HREF="http://parts.dkrz.de/">PARTS</A>
   
  <p>This is a project which will be funded in  the
      <a href="http://www.cordis.lu/fp5/home.html">European 
      Research Framework 5</a> of the European Commission

  <p>PARTS is part of the <a href="http://www.ozone-sec.ch.cam.ac.uk/clusters/Ocli_Website/ocli_euproj.html"> OCLI </a>  cluster

</center>
<p><hr>
<h2>The University of Oxford's role in PARTS </h2>
The role of the Atmospheric, Oceanic and Planetary Physics (AOPP) subgroup of the University of Oxford physics department is as following:
<li> to act as lead contractor to <A HREF="http://www.mpimet.mpg.de/Depts/Klima/adac/parts/optsat.html">WP2</A>, being responsible for the organisation of the scientific work;</li>
<li> to use measurements of WP2 along with existing refractive indices data to construct an algorithm to determine aerosol particle size from <A HREF="http://www-rab.larc.nasa.gov/">SAGE II</A> data.  SAGE II estimates of particle properties will be combined with those from the  <A HREF="http://www.atsr.rl.ac.uk/">ATSR/2</A> and<A HREF="http://umpgal.gsfc.nasa.gov/uars-science.html">UARS</A> instruments to produce a 20+ year dataset of aerosol properties in the UT/LS; </li>
<li>to provide satellite observations and to use them together with the  <A HREF="http://www.forst.uni-muenchen.de/LST/METEOR/stohl/astohl.html">Technische Universit&auml;t M&uuml;nchen (TUMUC)</A> to study the properties of aerosols in forest fire plumes in the UT/LS (<A HREF="http://www.mpimet.mpg.de/Depts/Klima/adac/parts/transp.html">WP3</A>).

<hr>
